2 SENATE BILL 668
1 Section 8–501 through 8–503 to be under the amended subtitle “Subtitle 5.
2 Children’s Cabinet Interagency Fund”
3 Annotated Code of Maryland
4 (2019 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
5 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
6 Article – Human Services
7 Section 8–504 through 8–506 and 8–508
8 Annotated Code of Maryland
9 (2019 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
10 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
11 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
12 Article – Education
13 8–417.
14 (b) (1) The Department, in collaboration with the fiscal agent of the Children’s
15 Cabinet INTERAGENCY Fund under Title 8, Subtitle 5 of the Human Services Article, shall
16 administer and implement a redesigned rate setting process for nonpublic general
17 education schools, residential child care programs, and nonresidential child care programs.
18 Article – Health – General
19 15–139.
20 (c) (1) For each fiscal year, the Governor may provide funds in the budget for
21 the Children’s Cabinet INTERAGENCY Fund established under Title 8, Subtitle 5 of the
22 Human Services Article, to be used by the Children’s Cabinet to create an interagency pool
23 of funds to provide services to children with disabilities.
24 Article – Human Services
25 Subtitle 5. Children’s Cabinet INTERAGENCY Fund.
26 8–501.
27 In this subtitle, “Fund” means the Children’s Cabinet INTERAGENCY Fund.
28 8–502.
29 There is a Children’s Cabinet INTERAGENCY Fund.
30 8–503.
31 (a) The Fund:

SENATE BILL 668 3
1 (1) consists of money appropriated, transferred, credited, or paid into the
2 Fund from any source; and
3 (2) includes money for out–of–home care and services to prevent
4 out–of–home placements.
5 (b) At the end of each fiscal year any unspent money in the Fund shall revert to
6 the General Fund.
7 (C) (1) THE GOVERNOR SHALL INCLUDE IN THE ANNUAL BUDGET BILL
8 THE FOLLOWING APPROPRIATIONS FOR THE FUND TO BE USED FOR GRANTS TO
9 ELIGIBLE LOCAL MANAGEMENT BOARDS:
10 (I) FOR FISCAL YEAR 2028, $3,000,000 $1,000,000 ABOVE THE
11 APPROPRIATION TO THE FUND IN FISCAL YEAR 2027;
12 (II) FOR FISCAL YEAR 2029, $2,000,000 $500,000 ABOVE THE
13 APPROPRIATION TO THE FUND IN FISCAL YEAR 2028;
14 (III) FOR FISCAL YEAR 2030, $2,000,000 $500,000 ABOVE THE
15 APPROPRIATION TO THE FUND IN FISCAL YEAR 2029; AND
16 (IV) FOR FISCAL YEAR 2031, $2,000,000 $500,000 ABOVE THE
17 APPROPRIATION TO THE FUND IN FISCAL YEAR 2030.
18 (2) MONEY EXPENDED FROM THE FUND FOR GRANTS TO ELIGIBLE
19 LOCAL MANAGEMENT BOARDS UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION IS
20 SUPPLEMENTAL TO AND NOT INTENDED TO TAKE THE PLACE OF FUNDING THAT
21 OTHERWISE WOULD BE EXPENDED FOR GRANTS TO ELIGIBLE LOCAL MANAGEMENT
22 BOARDS.
23 8–504.
24 Expenditures from the Fund shall be made:
25 (1) in accordance with the State Finance and Procurement Article; and
26 (2) to reflect the priorities, policies, and procedures that the Children’s
27 Cabinet adopts.
28 8–505.
29 (a) A local management board shall apply for money from the Fund in accordance
30 with procedures established by the Children’s Cabinet.

4 SENATE BILL 668
1 (b) In connection with an application for money under subsection (a) of this
2 section, a local management board shall develop and submit a community partnership
3 agreement that:
4 (1) reflects coordination with:
5 (i) the State’s 3–year plan for children, youth, and families; and
6 (ii) any local government plan for services for children, youth, and
7 families, including the local substance abuse plan developed in accordance with Title 8,
8 Subtitle 10 of the Health – General Article; and
9 (2) addresses the priorities and strategies of the county for meeting the
10 identified needs of children and families as articulated in the local management board’s
11 5–year strategic plan regarding:
12 (i) youth development;
13 (ii) prevention services;
14 (iii) crisis and early intervention;
15 (iv) services for children at risk of out–of–home placement or
16 returning from out–of–home placement; and
17 (v) out–of–home placement and treatment.
18 (c) The Children’s Cabinet may disburse money to a local management board
19 subject to the terms, conditions, performance measures, or outcome evaluations that the
20 Children’s Cabinet considers necessary.
21 (d) The local management board shall use the money to implement:
22 (1) a local interagency services delivery system for children, youth, and
23 families in accordance with the community partnership agreement; and
24 (2) any terms, conditions, and performance measures that the Children’s
25 Cabinet requires.
26 8–506.
27 (a) The State shall fund only evidence–based and promising home visiting
28 programs for improving parent and child outcomes, as provided in the State budget.
29 (b) Not less than 75% of the State funding for home visiting programs shall be
30 made available to evidence–based home visiting programs.

SENATE BILL 668 5
1 8–508.
2 The Governor’s Office for Children is the fiscal agent for the Fund.
3 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
4 1, 2026.
